  The wife of Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.says her husband shouldn't be counted out of the Democraticpresidential race or chastised for criticizing the other contendersfor the nomination.   His message is that he is the only Democratic candidate withexperience in both the federal government and foreign policy, Mrs.Gore said Wednesday during a series of stops in Indiana to helpkick off her husband's campaign for the May 3 Hoosier primary inwhich 79 delegates are at stake.   ``I think it's a three-man race,'' she said during a stop at aSalvation Army center in Indianapolis. ``I think we did very wellin Wisconsin considering we got a late start there.''   Gore polled 17 percent of the votes in Wisconsin to finish thirdbehind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson.   Gore was criticized by Jackson supporters after he said recentlythat Americans are choosing a president, not a preacher, and shouldlook at candidates' experience in public service.   ``He's just drawing the differences between his leadership andthe other candidates in the race,'' Mrs. Gore said.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Kean Says Equal Rights Amendment, Urban Issues Should Be In GOPPlatform</HEAD><DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Gov. Thomas H. Kean says he wants the EqualRights Amendment and urban issues to be addressed at the RepublicanNational Convention in August.   Kean made the remarks at an impromptu news conference followinga public ceremony in his outer office.   He said he has long pressed for the ERA to be a plank in the GOPplatform. At the party's convention in New Orleans, Kean said, hewill again push the amendment, as well as proposals to boost aid tocities and improve the quality of education.   Kean said he is ``trying to see that many of those things getinto the platform as possible'' although he acknowledged that``what does make a difference is what the candidate says, becausethat will be, in effect, the platform.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Robertson Scheduled to Address Nevada Convention</HEAD><DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Republican presidential hopeful Pat Robertsonwill speak here April 23 at the state GOP convention, where hisbackers are expected to dominate delegates to the state meeting,according to his Nevada coordinator.   Robertson is scheduled to speak on the final day of thethree-day session and may hold a fundraiser in Reno the eveningbefore, coordinator Steve Wark said on Wednesday.   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., will give the keynote address to theconvention. Other speakers scheduled are GOP National CommitteeChairman Frank Fahrenkopf of Reno. Nevada's Sen. Chic Hecht, Rep.Barbara Vucanovich and Attorney General Brian McKay are alsoscheduled to speak.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Conservatives Will Hold Out For Delegates Of Their Own Choosing</HEAD><DATELINE>OLYMPIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Washington's conservative Republicans concedeVice President George Bush will win a first ballot nomination to betheir party's presidential candidate.   But they say they still stand ready to fight for delegates oftheir own choosing because they believe Bush delegates might not beconservative enough.   ``We want to send delegates to the national convention thatbelieve in the traditional conservative set of principles that havegoverned the party in this state since 1976,'' said Steve Sego, whowas Sen. Bob Dole's Western-states coordinator.   ``Republicans in Washington State have steadfastly supported theReagan Revolution and its conservative principles. It's imperativethat we continue to support these principles in New Orleans,'' saidJim Summers, the Dole for President Washington State co-chairman.   This weekend the second phase of selection of 41 WashingtonRepublican delegates begins.</TEXT></DOC>